{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"538657e7-01da-4137-9048-6d99ba1f1634","content":"Use `#if` preprocessor directives with platform-specific compilation constants in `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\npublic static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()\n{\n    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();\n    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();\n\n#if ANDROID\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Android.AndroidNotificationService>();\n#elif IOS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.iOS.IosNotificationService>();\n#elif WINDOWS\n    builder.Services.AddSingleton<INotificationService, Platforms.Windows.WindowsNotificationService>();\n#endif\n\n    return builder.Build();\n}\n```\n\nEach implementation lives under its respective `Platforms/` folder (e.g., `Platforms/Android/AndroidNotificationService.cs`), which are already conditionally compiled per-platform via the default `.csproj` settings.\n\n**Why this is safe:** The `#if` directives ensure only the relevant platform code is compiled into each target binary, so there's no risk of referencing unavailable platform APIs at runtime.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9cae4602-f9ed-4989-bf2f-a981da1cd5b9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI dependency injection — specifically how to register platform-specific implementations of an `INotificationService` in `MauiProgram.cs`. This is a general knowledge question, not a codebase-specific task.","outputTokens":346},"id":"2045d447-6688-4419-b09f-bd3004705c11","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:41:32.771Z","parentId":"b08a8038-663f-4605-bff6-e0f9275e7256"}
